Pull up a seat at my Thanksgivjng table, friend. There's a new blog post up on Local Milk for Thanksgivjng! It has some decidedly NOT fall colored table inspiration (orange was never my thing), and a recipe for my new favorite holiday recipe / all the time party starter / breakfast bowl topper: Jammy Eggs with Homemade Kewpie Mayo & Furikake! Click the link in profile to join my table & steal my recipe while you're there!
üí´
Gratitude is the name of the game this week (and every week around here), and I've been thinking a lot about the different ways in which we can let gratitude escape us, in the good times and the bad. Because as any sensible person knows whether you have a million dollar business or you're just barely scraping by you are equally capable of being perfectly miserable or perfectly happy in either scenario.
üéÅ
When we have plenty‚Äîgood health, loving relationships, time & money‚Äîwe run the risk of taking it all for granted. Of falling prey to the voices in the world (and they are legion) that demand we want more, more, more. Which is why even in the good seasons of life, it's critical we practice gratitude.
üå©
And in the stormy seasons, it's easy to be blinded by the areas that are going wrong. But even in death, in illness, and in loss, we have the choice to choose hope & joy. To choose gratitude. To change the negative tapes playing in our head. Gratitude is always there for the taking. And it will transform your entire world.
üåà
Today, I'm grateful for my healthy, happy beautiful Eulalie. A working marriage with @matthewlud (like a working farm...this marriage doesn't just sit there looking pretty...it's real, beautiful work). A career I love and the ability to work and travel at the same time. And YOU, my friend. This whole thing would be nothing without you. Head over to the link in profile to read the whole blog post, see my table, and get the recipe! And let me me know in the comments: What are you grateful for? If it's a person tag them to let them know! #livemoremagic #localmilkgathering ‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢

On today's @rawmilkpodcast episode I'm talking about my LEAST favorite 4 letter F word...
üôÄ
FEAR. Namely how to get over fear and finally START something. That's right! The @rawmilkpodcast is back in action. Just click the link in profile to listen to the latest episode and head over to the @rawmilkpodcast feed for daily inspiration and motivation to make your dreams (like, for instance, calling your bedroom your office! üò¨) a reality!
‚ú®
Through the bumps & bruises to our heart during the normal course of life we develop fears that don't serve us. Fears based on false beliefs. I chose today's topic because I know exactly what that feels like.
üôà
After a 4 month break, I became intimately acquainted with the fear of starting again. Negative thoughts swirl. So you procrastinate on starting that business, that blog, that YouTube channel, that Etsy store, that podcast...You make excuses. And you never start. You don't try because if you don't try you can't fail. Many brilliant people never break past this wall.
‚ö°Ô∏è
The difference between people who make it and people who don't is not whether they fail or not. People who make it fail MORE than people who don't. Because they step out in fear, into the unknown, and try. And get up and try again.
‚ú®
And that's what it is to be brave. You don't expect fear to go away entirely. But you jump anyway. And in today's episode I'll teach you how. If you love the episode, share some love in the review section on iTunes and follow @rawmilkpodcast here on Instagram to help us climb the charts after my sabbatical! I do the podcast weekly for 100% free and your reviews, likes, and comments are what keep us going! If I know I'm helping people, that's all the motivation I need! So tune in and join me in saying my favorite four letter F word (you can guess that one!) to my least favorite four letter F word, fear! üòÇ #ff ‚Ä¢

Go steal my recipe (along with my homemade kewpie and furikake recipes!) via the link in profile on the Local Milk blog! And don't forget to enter the giveaway for a free pack of my new Lightroom presets for mobile and desktop, The Instagram Collection! It closes Monday! See my previous post for details! And happy holiday weekend...may you all be doing a whole lot of nothing & have leftovers for dayyyzzz.

"The only way out is in." My mantra today. A quote from this morning's yoga practice. Sometimes the jungle and the secret garden are one and the same. The only thing to change is your eyes, and to change your eyes you have to go inside yourself. What I hope for you today...
‚Ä¢
I hope your body serves you. Whether it's walking, stretching, or simply being in less pain than the day before, I hope you and your body are in a conversation. Lean into the challenge, the sweat, the pain. Listen. Your body is where the mind begins.
‚Ä¢
I hope you have the simple pleasure of tasting something that nourishes your body or soul and brings you pleasure. A bright smoothie. A bowl of lentils. A perfectly cooked egg. A clean, clear glass of water. Campari. Cheese pizza. Whatever. I hope it tastes good and you can care that it does. And that it feeds your cells or lifts your spirit or both.
‚Ä¢
And I hope you'll remember you don't have to be perfect to be beautiful. I don't know about you, but nothing and no one I've ever loved deeply was perfect. They were always pretty damn interesting though. Remember that in different seasons of life the same scene can fill you with joy or sadness. My hope for you today is that you'll see the light, be the light, laugh like at hell at my banalities and feel better and think "those leaves look nice and glow." What is your mantra today? #livemoremagic ‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
Ps. The mobile presets are coming but we wanted to make them perfect! SO many of you have asked (and yes this was edited with them!)....hang tight and they'll be the best they can be! üòò

Do you want to know what my number one priority in raising this little fairy angel is?
‚ú®
It's that she be brave. To be kind in this world, we must first be brave. That she know the difference between healthy fear and bad fear. That she have a bright inner North Star. I want her to understand that in life some cliffs should not be jumped off of because there are rocks below. And that from other cliffs you can dive into the glittering, aqua sea, no matter how scary it may seem when you're looking down.
üí´
On the latest episode of my show, the @rawmilkpodcast (follow along over there for daily motivation and inspiration in achieving your creative dreams!) that's what I'm talking about: How to Overcome Fear and Start. Whether it's a blog, an online business, a YouTube channel, an Instagram account, or a podcast...The first step is the leap. Everything afterwards becomes easier.
üåà
Click the link in profile to listen...and binge out on the other 15 episodes if you haven't listened before! It's a great way to pass the time during your holiday travels and hopefully it will give you the tools and motivation to tell your fear to take the backseat so you can bravely step out and pursue your dreams without letting a bunch of false beliefs in your way!
üëáüèª
Let me know in the comments what else you'd like to hear on the show! I'm an open book on all things creative business, making money as a creative (and not needing to apologize for it!), online & social media marketing, and more!

"The image was taken while driving across The Alvord Desert in Oregon," the photographer Jono Melamed (@le_yone). "After a few rough months, I drove down to The Alvord to get away from everything that was holding me down at home in the city. There are no roads on the playa‚Ä¶ No roads and no rules. So, I drove‚Ä¶ Fast‚Ä¶ With loud music playing and wind beating on my face. It was perfect and, for a brief moment, all of my problems melted away into the blur of the passing desert." The artist captions the image with this passage: "Sometimes it‚Äôs hard to remember that life is in front of you, even when you‚Äôre speeding away from the past." More at @le_yone. // #contemporaryphotography #artphotography #wanderlust #documentingspace #cinematicphotography #beautifuldestinations #traveldeeper #landscapephotography #mindtheminimal #landscapelovers #ig_minimalistic #landscapes #landscape_specialist #minimalmood #landscapecaptures #landscape_lovers #travelmemories #travelgram #minimalphotography #minimalism #naturegram #ontheroadagain #naturalworld #travelphotography #ontheroad #americanroads #americanlandscape #great_captures_minimal #americanroadtrip #minimallandscape

"I took this photo from a hotel room with a window overlooking the very center of Warsaw," Ada Zieli≈Ñska (@adsoadsoadso) remembers. "It was November 11th, 2018, the day when Poland celebrated a century of independence. The gathering you can see from the window is the beggining of annual Independence March. For this occasion, I booked the room to stage this photo. A week earlier, I checked view from every floor in the hotel, and finally I decided on the 9th floor, room 919. The idea was to contrast the cosy interior with the vivid, loud and sometimes violent celebration. I asked the calmest person I know to pose for this photo, and suggested she to wear the most comfortable clothes. We entered the room, rearranged it so the bed was next to the window, and just waited there for Warsaw to dissapear in flares. I took two exposures from the room and put them into one photo." While she prefers not to comment politically, the viral photograph has been read by some as a reflection of current unease in Europe. You can see more, including footage from the day, at @adsoadsoadso. // #contemporaryphotography #popsofcolor #cinematicphotography #surrealphotography #environmentalportrait #cinematic #architectureandpeople #mistyfoggymilkymoody #portraitperfection #makeportraits #portraitphotography #nightmoves #nightphotography #nightphoto

"In 1996, after returning from the U.S.-Mexico border, I showed this photograph to Rebecca [Norris Webb], who I‚Äôd been seeing for some six months," Alex Webb (@webb_norriswebb) writes. "'Muy romantico,' she said, smiling bemusedly. Looking again at this photograph from Nuevo Laredo, Mexico, I began to see what she saw ‚Äî that the image strikes a different note. Although inhabited by those deep shadows that characterize much of my Mexico work, this particular photograph is quieter, more lyrical. It‚Äôs as if its human moments ‚Äî the couple embracing, the father holding his child ‚Äî somehow manage to keep the darkness at bay, even if only briefly. Photographers don‚Äôt just find photographs; sometimes photographs find photographers. In retrospect, it hardly seems surprising that this photograph found me when it did ‚Äî as I was falling for the remarkable woman and lyrical photographer who‚Äôs the love of my life. Three years later, we printed this photograph on our wedding invitations." This image is part of 'Slant Rhymes', a book of photography and poetry by Webb and Norris Webb. It‚Äôs been exactly three years since I took the picture of a young Syrian refugee while passing through Rigonce in Slovenia. Unfortunately, the situation hasn‚Äôt improved much but only moved to the border between Bosnia and Croatia.
This Friday evening the whole series will be on show in a special group exhibition of Slovenian contemporary photography ‚ÄòIf Slovenia Were‚Äô curated by @klavdijsluban at @gradrajhenburg in Brestanica very close to the border with Croatia.
You are most kindly invited to the opening of our exhibition at 7pm. It‚Äôs exactly 1h drive away from Zagreb and Ljubljana.
The exhibition will be on view until April 21, 2019.

Tshering‚Äôs camp sits under Mt. Masanggang, at about 4,500 m above sea level. Light in the tent is turned on during dinner time. Even though it‚Äôs July, it gets very cold during the night; temperatures here at 4,500 m above sea level can fall below zero degrees Celsius. The main problems faced by Tshering's family are the rapidly changing climate and wild predator attacks. More in the @natgeo story in my profile.

When we first arrived at a summer yak herding camp at the base of Mt. Masangang, all I could see were female yaks, which are similar in size to European cows. It was not until the evening that the fifty-year-old yak herder, Tshering, rounded up all the male yaks.
Their sight took my breath away because these creatures seemed like they had just arrived from another planet. There was very heavy rainfall, and they were running to our camp from all possible corners of the mountain. Tshering told me to stay out of the way and be very careful with my movements.
Tshering and his family live in the camp five months a year and spend the rest in Laya. They have 20 male and 20 female yaks. While male yak is mainly used for transportation, ploughing field, clothing and tents, the female yak is mainly intended for milk. Read @natgeo story with a link in my profile to learn more.

A view of the retreating Masangang Glacier at the Mt. Masangang from a yak summer camp at 4,500m above the sea level. A yak herding family moves to the camp and lives there for about five months every summer. The rest of the year they stay in the hometown of Laya in Bhutan. Tshering, the father of the family, told me that 25 years ago glaciers were very solid and numerous. He commented: ‚ÄúWe didn't do anything but they are melting fast.‚Äù Read the @natgeo story with a link in my profile to learn more.

A solar panel used to charge mobile phones at a yak summer camp at the base of Mt. Masangang 4,500m above the sea level. Once carbon neutral Bhutan has now become the only carbon negative country in the world absorbing more carbon from the air than releasing. The climate change is disrupting the small nation‚Äôs fragile ecosystem. Even though the small nation of Bhutan is hardly responsible for most of the world's greenhouse gases, the country is responding by doubling down on its already impressive environmental regulations. Read the @natgeo story with a link in my profile to learn more.

Yak herder Tshering and his son Karma are leading a caravan from the village of Laya, the highest settlement in the country, to Gasa, a valley town that is two days of walking away. They use horses and mules to carry the bags with their equipment and goods for trading. Follow link in my profile to read @natgeo story published earlier this year.

This was one of those magical mornings. I woke up from my tent in this simply incredible scenery with Himalayan glaciers surrounding our base. Tshering‚Äôs camp sits under Mt. Masanggang, at about 4,500 m above sea level. His wife Om, 43, is taking care of female yaks. Every morning they milk most of them; some of the milk is later used to make cheese. Om‚Äôs daughter, Sangay Yangdon, is 13 and is helping her mother during her school holiday week. Read the @natgeo story with a link in my profile to learn more.

We sat down to drink some warm yak milk after a 10h trekking to the yak summer camp at the Mt. Masangang. Tshering, the father of the family, talked about his family, his two wives, and expressed a concern about the scarcity of water resources for the future generations. Read the @natgeo story with a link in my profile to learn more.

I am excited to be at the International Conference on the Biodivsersity of Papua (ICBE 2018) in Manokwari this week with Ed Scholes representing the @BirdsofparadiseProject with like-minded people who are working to promote conservation in Papua and West Papua Provinces.

Indonesia‚Äôs provinces of Papua and West Papua on island of New Guinea make up the Land of Papua or "Tanah Papua" in the Indonesian language. This region supports one of the only remaining large tropical forests in the world and is home to nearly half of Indonesia‚Äôs biodiversity. Over 600 species of birds are found in Papua, including 27 bird-of-paradise species, many of which live nowhere else on earth. Global interest in Papua‚Äôs birdlife is leading to increased opportunity for wildlife tourism and bringing newfound economic benefits to local communities. Sustainable development is not only important for the future of Papua‚Äôs forests and people, but also for the world.
The Cornell Lab‚Äôs Birds-of-Paradise Project is working with the Governments of Papua and West Papua and other international partners to further science, engagement and conservation of the region‚Äôs biodiversity with a focus on the birds-of-paradise.
#RajaAmpat, #Waigeo, #Papua, #Indonesia, #TanahPapua, #PapuaBiodiversity, #RedBirdofParadise, #BirdofParadise.

Hi and Happy Thanksgiving everyone. I know many of you have been following my work on the Birds-of-Paradise for many years. Now there is a chance for you to make a difference for these amazing birds, and all the biodiversity of Papua, where species like this incredible Red Bird-of-Paradise live. As I have mentioned in some recent posts, the government of West Papua, Indonesia, has declared their intent to be a ‚ÄúConservation Province‚Äù or ‚ÄúProvinsi Konservasi‚Äù in Indonesian, and protect 70% of their land as forest, as well as protect vast marine areas. In December, there will an important vote in the Provincial government taking place to make this Conservation Province declaration into law, which is a very important first step in actually putting this noble goal into practice. People all over the world can support this cause by simply signing a petition to let the government of Papua know that we are aware of the amazing conservation leadership they are taking and wish to support and encourage them. Please go to the link in my IG profile, or this link https://www.sealegacy.org/pages/west-papua?utm_source=tlaman&utm_campaign=westpapua&utm_content=petition and sign the petition organized by our good friends at @SeaLegacy, to help reach the goal of 30,000 signatures. Photo by @TimLaman. A wild female orangutan in Borneo crosses a fallen tree making a natural bridge over a river. This is a new camera trap shot I just got on my recent visit to Gunung Palung National Park in Indonesian Borneo. I was there checking on my ongoing @NatGeo project to try to document the less well known nocturnal mammals. But in this case, I captured an orangutan female instead, actually carrying a baby on her belly (that is hard to see except its orange fur) who was being chased by bees and came down to the ground. In Season 4, Episode 5 of HOKA One One Top Trails, we visit the North Carolina Research Triangle- a region comprised of Raleigh, Durham, and Chapel Hill. -
In Durham, Alex Tallman (Fleet Feet Retail Experience Trainer) takes us on a run on the American Tobacco Trail, which was formerly a railroad used to take tobacco to the warehouses in town.  Alex talks about his recent move to Durham, and shift in careers. He also discusses how being a part of the running community has been a great way to become familiar with a new city, participating in group runs like the Ponysaurus Pub Run and the Vecino Pub Run.
-
In Raleigh, Andy Chang (Fleet Feet Raleigh/Morrisville ) discusses the largest trail system in the Research Triangle- Umstead State Park.  Chang tells us about what Umstead and the Research Triangle have to offer for wooded, single-track trails.
-
In Chapel Hill / Carrboro, Sean Bezdek (Fleet Feet Carrboro) runs the trails of Carolina North Forest. Sean discusses how he got into running, leaving behind a difficult family situation and the unhealthy lifestyle he was living as a sponsored skateboarder.
-
Watch the full show at toptrail.runnerspace.com!
-

Just completed this new work for our on going mental health project @onedayinmyworld . please check out the full story through the link in my profile. -
One of life‚Äôs greatest misconceptions is a simple fable. That time is a healer. One year ago on the 25th of August ‚Äúethnic cleansing‚Äù perpetrated by the Burmese military sparked the world‚Äôs greatest refugee crisis. Now nearly a million Rohingya, those who escaped the flames and executions, are living in camps in Bangladesh. Many of these survivors were raped, most saw loved ones killed, thousands arrived wounded. All are traumatized. Here, in this impoverished monsoon soaked corner of Bangladesh, is the most densely populated area of PTSD affected and depressed people on earth. Here, time has not healed. ‚ÄúThey said that there was another bomb so I laid low and began to crawl,‚Äù says 30-year-old Yabintu who sells food in a market in Konduga in Borno state, Nigeria. ‚ÄúAs I crawled, I realized that my body was pierced in many places, and I continued until I hid in the nearby bush.‚Äù The suspected bomb blast that killed many people in the market left her with injuries to her legs, arm and head. .

A look back at work I made in Lagos, Nigeria: Sand dug from the bottom of Lagos Lagoon is used to reclaim land and to make the concrete blocks many of the city‚Äôs houses are made from. Much of that sand is dug by hand. These are sand miners who dive 4 ‚Äì 5 metres to the bottom of the lagoon and, one bucket at a time, fill the boats powered by wind - propelled with sails made of rice sacks. My fixer regularly risked his welfare while working with me in Lagos - but coming out on the water on these stitched together boats was too much of a stretch - he stayed on shore.

I started @WhereLoveIsIllegal because I wanted to contribute towards the fight against homophobia and transphobia. I had heard about homophobic laws and read the reports from human rights group condemning them, but rarely did I hear from the targets of this discrimination. Believing that people can be moved when they come to know survivors of abuse, I thought photography and storytelling might contribute towards creating a connection that might lead to action.
Most of Where Love Is Illegal's stories have been of difficulties faced. But many also have been of great resilience, and love found, despite massive challenges. Recent work made in collaboration with The Elton John Aids Foundation was no different - stories of terrible suffering, but also of incredible courage and of love. Of course, it should never have to take courage to be with the person you love, but in many many places around the world, for hundreds of thousands of people it does.
We‚Äôll be sharing our new work at @WhereLoveIsIllegal. Please follow along.

Photo @hammond_robin Nightmares take 12 year old Rohingya refugee Johura back to the day 14 of her 16 family members were killed. But her most regular dream is of eating a meal with her mother and sister in their Myanmar village. What food do you like? ‚ÄúI don‚Äôt feel hungry.‚Äù Ever? ‚ÄúIf I feel very hungry I have a little rice.‚Äù Why don‚Äôt you enjoy eating? ‚ÄúWhen I think of my parents I don‚Äôt feel good eating.‚Äù Do you think about them often? ‚ÄúYes. I do. With every breath I take.‚Äù Johura was semi-conscious much of the journey from Myanmar to Bangladesh. She had lost a lot of blood from a bullet that struck her hip. Fortune briefly shone on her during this nightmare. From the shoulder of the man carrying her she shook awake to see a group of boys - one of them her 10-year-old brother - her only surviving sibling. And there is her light - the glimmer of hope in which she might find peace. Neither food, nor friends, nor playing, nor pretty dresses make her happy. How about you brother, does your brother make you happy? ‚ÄúIf my brother is happy, that can make me happy - in here, he is the only one who can.‚Äù // One of life‚Äôs greatest misconceptions is a simple fable. That time is a healer. One year ago this week ‚Äúethnic cleansing‚Äù perpetrated by the Myanmar military against the Rohingya sparked a massive refugee crisis. Nearly a million Rohingya ‚Äì those who escaped the flames and executions ‚Äì are now living in camps in Bangladesh. Many of them were raped, most saw loved ones killed, thousands arrived wounded. All are traumatized. Here, in this impoverished monsoon soaked corner of Bangladesh, is one of the most densely populated areas of PTSD affected and depressed people on earth. // This work was made in collaboration with M√©decins Sans Fronti√®res @doctorswithoutborders who provide mental health support to refugees and the local population. As a gay man in Ghana, everyday, where he goes, how he talks, walks, dresses must be carefully considered. It has made him a leader in the LGBTQI+ community and a healthcare advocate. Phi-phi Islands, atau yang dalam bahasa Thailand dinamakan "Koh Phi-phi" merupakan kepulauan yang terletak di bagian selatan Thailand, 38 km dari arah krabi. Phi-phi Islands dapat dikatakan salah satu destinasi terbaik bagi para wisatawan yang berkunjung ke Thailand. Mulai dari keindahan pantai putih diantara tebing-tebing Karst, hingga pesta pantai sepanjang malam bersama penduduk lokal dan para wisatawan lainnya. Jika anda berkunjung ke Thailand, jangan sampai melewatkan pulau yang cantik ini. .
sumber : https://blog.dwidayatour.co.id/blogpage/berlibur-ke-phi-phi-islands-surga-bagi-para-wisatawan-di-thailand-selatan

Kawah Wurung adalah sebuah kawasan perbukitan yang memiliki hamparan padang rumput (savana) yang hijau dengan cerukan yang berbentuk seperti kawah gunung. Perbukitan tersebut dikelilingi sebuah lubang raksasa seperti kaldera. Kawah Wurung berarti kawah yang tidak jadi atau bisa diartikan kawah yang telah mati. Kalau sebuah kawah umumnya terdapat air atau endapan belerang dengan buih-buihnya, maka di sini sepanjang mata memandang yang terlihat hanyalah perbukitan yang diselimuti rerumputan hijau diselingi dengan sedikit pepohonan di beberapa bagiannya.
.
sumber : http://www.banyuwangibagus.com/2016/06/pesona-bukit-kawah-wurung-bak-hamparan-permadani-hijau.html?m=1

Pulau Coron adalah pulau terbesar ketiga di Kepulauan Calamian di utara Palawan di Filipina. Pulau ini adalah bagian dari munisipalitas dengan nama yang sama yang lebih besar wilayahnya. Pulau ini berada sekitar 170 nautical miles (310 km) sebelah barat daya Manila dan dikenal karena adanya beberapa rongsokan kapal Jepang peninggalan dari Perang Dunia II. Karena bentuk ekologisnya yang unik, pulau ini sepenuhnya dilindungi oleh beberapa ketentuan hukum.
.
Sumber: Wikipedia
Lokasi: Coron, Palawan

Keindahan Situ Cilembang terletak pada airnya yang berwarna biru seperti terkena cat seorang pelukis yang tidak sengaja tumpah. Namun, sebenarnya warna sejati Situ Cilembang adalah jernih bersih. Warna biru situ mungil ini merupakan pantulan warna langit yang diterjemahkan secara sempurna oleh air Situ Cilembang yang sama sekali belum terkontaminasi.Tak mengherankan kalau air situ ini sangat bersih karena pada dasarnya tempat ini adalah sebuah mata air yang merupakan sumber air bagi warga sekitar. .

Gardens by the Bay boleh jadi merupakan taman yang paling luas dan paling indah di Singapura, dengan luas lahan lebih dari 100 hektar dan memiliki lebih dari 1 juta koleksi tanaman.  Gardens by the Bay yang terletak di sebelah Marina reservoir dan di belakang Hotel Marina Bay Sands sudah menjadi ikon pariwisata Singapura yang tidak boleh anda lewatkan untuk anda kunjungi ketika berada di Singapura.
